The Benefits section asserts that faster removals will create “large gains in agency efficiency” but admits OPM “does not have a reasonable basis for estimating the magnitude.” E.O. 12866 requires the agency to quantify benefits where feasible.  At minimum, OPM can draw on:

  - MSPB survey data on supervisor time lost to poor performers;  
  - FDIC Special Counsel report quantifying misconduct-related costs;  
  - GAO’s 2015 estimate ($350 million/yr) of “desk-duty” employees.

Why were these readily available sources ignored?  Absent monetized benefits, OPM cannot show the rule is cost-justified, nor that it qualifies as an E.O. 14192 “deregulatory action.”  The final rule must supply concrete dollar values or explain, with record evidence, why monetization is impossible.

